                    },
                    "html": {
                        "href": "https://bitbucket.org/yt_analysis/yt/pull-requests/1834"
                    }
                },
                "id": 1834
            },
            "content": {
                "raw": "I agree that this is a clear long-term improvement goal for the install script, and allows us to do this in a transparent way for users (although we will probably change the user experience in the install script a lot!). I think we should let the user select:\n\n* which yt version (stable, dev, yt-2.x, a specific version of changeset which maybe encourages reproducibility and verifiability? Allows us to quickly explain the difference between stable and dev.)\n* which PYTHON_VERSION (defaults to 2.7 probably, but allows 3.4 or 3.5)\n* INSTALL_FROM_ANACONDA (0 or 1)\n* MINICONDA_VERSION (defaults to 'latest'?)\n\nAnd then bring over all the other options from the regular `install_script.sh`. Turning on certain things (rockstar? Things that depend on GPL libraries?) might require the source installation. We would probably also build from the source installation to test yt on fido.\n\nI think this can be done, and is something we should plan on doing in the short to medium term to provide a better user experience when getting the code. On the other hand, it will definitely take a bit of work, so for now we should merge this in once I've updated it to suggest setenv for csh-style shells. If people have issues installing yt on the mailing list (particularly if they're on OSX 10.11), we can point to the current get_yt.sh script.\n\nMaybe we should write a tiny little curses interface? Is that portable on OSX and linux?",
                "html": "<p>I agree that this is a clear long-term improvement goal for the install script, and allows us to do this in a transparent way for users (although we will probably change the user experience in the install script a lot!). I think we should let the user select:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>which yt version (stable, dev, yt-2.x, a specific version of changeset which maybe encourages reproducibility and verifiability? Allows us to quickly explain the difference between stable and dev.)</li>\n<li>which PYTHON_VERSION (defaults to 2.7 probably, but allows 3.4 or 3.5)</li>\n<li>INSTALL_FROM_ANACONDA (0 or 1)</li>\n<li>MINICONDA_VERSION (defaults to 'latest'?)</li>\n</ul>\n<p>And then bring over all the other options from the regular <code>install_script.sh</code>. Turning on certain things (rockstar? Things that depend on GPL libraries?) might require the source installation. We would probably also build from the source installation to test yt on fido.</p>\n<p>I think this can be done, and is something we should plan on doing in the short to medium term to provide a better user experience when getting the code. On the other hand, it will definitely take a bit of work, so for now we should merge this in once I've updated it to suggest setenv for csh-style shells. If people have issues installing yt on the mailing list (particularly if they're on OSX 10.11), we can point to the current get_yt.sh script.</p>\n<p>Maybe we should write a tiny little curses interface? Is that portable on OSX and linux?</p>",
                "markup": "markdown"
            },
